  <h1>{frontmatter.title}</h1>

  <p>
    The traditional manufacturing model — centralized factories, long supply chains, massive minimum orders — doesn't work for small communities. Atlantic Canada knows this better than most. When you need 50 custom parts for a local business, the options have historically been: wait weeks for overseas shipping, or pay a premium to a single local shop with limited capacity.
  </p>

  <h2>The Distributed Model</h2>

  <p>
    3D3D operates as a distributed maker network. Instead of one central facility, we coordinate local makers across New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, PEI, and Newfoundland. Each maker runs their own printer fleet from home workshops, garages, and small studios.
  </p>

  <p>
    When an order comes in, it gets routed to the nearest available maker with the right material and capacity. The maker prints it, packages it, and ships directly to the customer. This network-based approach eliminates the bottlenecks of traditional manufacturing while keeping production local and responsive.
  </p>

  <h2>Why It Works</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Speed.</strong> With makers spread across the region, most orders ship within 24-48 hours. No waiting for production runs or container ships. A customer in Moncton can receive a custom part printed in Moncton — not shipped from a warehouse in Toronto or overseas.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Cost.</strong> Home-based makers have low overhead. No factory rent, no massive equipment loans. This keeps prices competitive while supporting local manufacturing jobs. Customers get fair pricing without the markup of traditional retail supply chains.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Resilience.</strong> If one maker's printer goes down, orders route to the next nearest maker. The network is self-healing. During supply chain disruptions in 2025, distributed networks like ours kept orders flowing while centralized shops struggled with parts shortages.
  </p>

  <h2>The Economics</h2>

  <p>
    For customers, the distributed model means better pricing on custom work. Traditional machine shops charge setup fees and minimums that make small runs impractical. A network of makers can handle one-off orders at scale — each maker does their part, and the customer gets exactly what they need without paying for idle machine time.
  </p>

  <p>
    For makers, the network provides a steady stream of work without the overhead of finding customers, handling payments, or managing support. Makers focus on what they do best: printing quality parts.
  </p>

  <p>
    This model aligns incentives. When customers get great parts quickly, they come back. When makers get consistent work, they invest in better equipment. The network grows stronger with every successful order.
  </p>

  <h2>Events and On-Location Printing</h2>

  <p>
    Beyond the maker network, 3D3D brings 3D printing directly to events. Content creator Ken runs live printing demonstrations at festivals, markets, and conventions across Atlantic Canada. Attendees watch their designs print in real-time and take home custom souvenirs.
  </p>

  <p>
    This event-based approach showcases the speed and flexibility of distributed manufacturing. People see the process firsthand — from digital model to physical object in minutes. It's manufacturing as entertainment, education, and commerce combined.
  </p>

  <h2>What's Next</h2>

  <p>
    We're expanding the network throughout 2026. The distributed model works — any region with a critical mass of 3D printer owners can form a network node. Our order routing, quality tracking, and coordination tools are ready to scale.
  </p>

